<div type="definition">
<p>BEAUTIFUL so as to CAUSE OTHERS TO TEND to DESIRE to COPULATE WITH ONE.</p>
    </div>
<div type="notes">
<div type="old-chinese-criteria">
<p>1. The general noun is sè 色 "female beauty" which seems to be used only in nominal functions.</p>
<p>2. The specific "adjective" would be yàn 艷 / 豔 which comes as close to "sexy" as any ancient Chinese word. ZUO: 美而艷</p>
<p>3. Jiǎo 姣 (also applied to men) and jiāo 嬌 are less dramatic than yàn 艷 and refer to personal charm as well beauty as such.</p>
<p>4. Yǎo tiǎo 窈窕 is the standard poetic cliche word for female attractiveness.</p>
<p>5. Mèi 媚 "seductively beautiful" includes an idea of deliberate acting or deliberate use of make-up to please someone. See FLATTER.</p>
<p>6. Kuā 姱 "lovely" is a highly poetic SHI and CC word of little currency in prose writing.</p>
        </div>
